Commentary.Commentary: We are back for India's reply! The players are making their way out to the middle now and the Kiwis spread out to take their respective field positions. Yashasvi Jaiswal and Rohit Sharma are the two openers for India. Matt Henry has the new red cherry in his hand and is raring to go. Let's play...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

New Zealand will feel like they are a few runs short after opting to bat first. They were rocked early losing Devon Conway but Will Young and Tom Latham steadied the ship for a while. It was not easy to bat on this wicket with the heat, but Young and Daryl Mitchell were the two batters who showed great commitment and resilience to the Indian spin attack. Both of them scored half-centuries and it was their partnership of 87 runs that have put them in this position where they can put up a good fight. If you don't remember, the last time when Ajaz Patel played at Wankhede in a Test, it was in 2021, and he took all 10 wickets against India in the first innings. The Kiwis will be hoping for something similar to put pressure back on the hosts. Join us in a bit for India's reply.

A solid bowling performance from India! They have restricted New Zealand to 235 with Ravindra Jadeja leading the pack with an excellent five-wicket haul. Akash Deep made the early breakthrough, but then it was all about the spinners with the wicket also assisting them. There were a few moments when the hosts had to be patient and on a wicket like this, you have to do that and not overattack. Their patience was rewarded and the start from the previous game, Washington Sundar ended up with four wickets and wrapped things up as well.

OUT! LBW! A huge confident appeal by everyone surrounding the batter and the umpire raises his finger instantly. Ajaz Patel though has reviewed it and challenged the on-field decision. He is in danger though as no shot is offered. Washington Sundar finishes with a spectacular 4-fer. Sundar comes from around the stumps and bowls it around off and drifts it into the batter off the pitch. Ajaz Patel takes a good stride across and looks to pad it away offering no shot at it. Ball Tracking comes up and clearly shows three reds. New Zealand have been bowled out on 235 with 20 overs or so remaining in the day.

OUT! TAKEN! What a magnificent catch by Rohit Sharma at the first slip. An absolute stunner from the Indian skipper. Washington Sundar bowls from over the stumps and flattens the trajectory, bowls it on a good length, around middle and off channel. Daryl Mitchell is quick to rock back and squats at it to guide it through the short third region but is beaten by the pace and just tries to guide it with soft hands. Opens the bat face and ends up slicing it off the outer half. The ball goes flat and low towards the first slip. Rohit Sharma shows good reflexes and is quick to react and takes a sharp catch to his right.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for the final session of the first day! It continues to stay humid and unforgivingly warm in Mumbai. The umpires are punctual to walk out and so are the Indian players who take their respective field positions after a brief team talk near the ropes. Daryl Mitchell unbeaten on a gutsy 53 off 96 walks out to resume with the bat with Ish Sodhi. It will be Washington Sundar (13-2-50-2) to get the proceedings underway in the third session with the ball. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

New Zealand got through the first hour of the session without losing any wickets. Will Young and Daryl Mitchell looked settled and scored at a good rate too with the former also getting to his first fifty of the series. However, their resistance was finally broken by Ravindra Jadeja when the stand was worth 87. He added two more pretty quickly with the Kiwis going from 159/3 to 187/6. Mitchell though held one end solidly staying unbeaten on 53 despite struggling a lot with the heat. He is the key for New Zealand if they want to get anything near 250, but India knows they have a long tail and will want to wrap things up quickly in the next session. Join us in about 20 minutes to see how things unfold in the final session.

SESSION SUMMARY - 100 runs and 3 wickets in 28 overs! A hard-fought session with both teams battling it out in the middle in the excessive heat of Mumbai. These are very challenging conditions and with the pitch offering turn and bounce, batting is not easy at all. However, the Kiwis have shown good commitment and are not making it easy for the hosts.
Jadeja wraps the session with a full-length delivery around off, Ish Sodhi strides ahead and eases it to mid on. And that will be TEA ON DAY 1!

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for the post-Lunch session, folks! The sun shines to its glory and greets the two umpires who make their way out to the middle. Indian players too, spread out to the field. Will Young, unbeaten on 38 will resume his innings with Daryl Mitchell. And it will be Washington Sundar (8-1-26-2) to start the proceedings after Lunch. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

Well then, India have managed to get an early upper hand in this game but this Test match is just warming up! The post-Lunch session - traditionally the best time to bat on - could be New Zealand's chance to counter-punch. Young's still standing firm and resolute, and the Kiwis will be eyeing this window to shift gears and steady their ship. India on the other hand, with the ball gripping and jumping, they'll be hunting for more scalps to build on their morning's success. An exciting second session coming up next. It will begin right after 40 minutes at 6.40 am GMT. Stay tuned.

As the pitch began to bare its teeth, runs came at a premium. The Kiwi batters unleashed their sweep shots arsenal to combat the vicious turn and bounce, but India's bowlers had their tails up. The surface showed glimpses of a rank-turner, and despite the batters' best efforts to innovate, it was India's bowlers who were calling the shots.

Credit to the Kiwis though – they kept the scoreboard moving, avoiding a maiden until the 16th over. But as the session wore on, India's spinners found their rhythm, extracting both grip and bounce. Young stood firm against the turning ball, but New Zealand desperately needed another solid partnership to build on. The surface was beginning to reveal its true colors, heavily supporting the turners, and surviving wasn't going to get any easier. Overall, it was Sundar who turned the screws, claiming two scalps with some absolute jaffas off the deck, also dismissing Ravindra for the third time in this series.

India's pace duo made their presence felt from the word go. Akash Deep was particularly impressive, generating extra bounce and zip off the deck even without much swing on offer. While he and Siraj laid the foundation with probing spells, it was Sundar who delivered the breakthrough, breaking the growing Latham-Young's 44-run resistance for the second wicket.

New Zealand rolled the dice to bat first, braving humid and energy-sapping conditions and a tricky surface. It wasn't that good surface to bat on as anticipated. Conway's early exit in the third over set alarm bells ringing, but Latham and Young dug in, crafting a determined 44-run partnership against India's spin tandem before the skipper perished after getting a good decent start.

LUNCH, DAY 1 - Session Summary - 27 overs, 92 runs, 3 wickets. In all fairness, India would be quite pleased with their bowling display as the players walk off the field for Lunch. Also, the over rate has been bang on, with someone like Jadeja bowling, who completes his overs at an express pace. New Zealand on the other hand, have been rocked early as they have lost their top order in a jiffy, including the in-form Rachin Ravindra.
Quicker, full and on middle, Daryl Mitchell keeps it out well. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!

Commentary.Commentary: Well then, all in readiness for this final Test to commence at Wankhede. It is typically sunny and humid Mumbai weather which greets the two umpires who make their way out to the middle. The Indian team is in a huddle, and Rohit Sharma is providing his words of wisdom before they spread out to take the field. Devon Conway and Tom Latham, the two openers for New Zealand are already out to the middle awaiting the fielders to spread out. Latham will face the first delivery and it will be Mohammed Siraj to bowl the first over for India. Three slips and a gully for him to begin with. And, here we go...

India (Playing XI) - Rohit Sharma (C), Yashasvi Jaiswal, Shubman Gill, Virat Kohli, Rishabh Pant (WK), Sarfaraz Khan, Ravindra Jadeja, Ravichandran Ashwin, Washington Sundar, Akash Deep, Mohammed Siraj (IN FOR JASPRIT BUMRAH).

New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham (C), Devon Conway, Will Young, Rachin Ravindra, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Glenn Phillips, Ish Sodhi (IN FOR MITCHELL SANTNER), Matt Henry (IN FOR TIM SOUTHEE), Ajaz Patel, William O'Rourke.

Rohit Sharma, the captain of India says that they haven't played well in this series. Adds that it is a good pitch and is hopeful that they will restrict them from running away. On being asked about the World Test Championship standings, he says that they are taking one game at a time and the focus right now is on this game only. Also says that in the back of the mind, you need to look at what lies ahead, but it is important to stay in the present. Informs that Jasprit Bumrah is not well and Mohammed Siraj comes in for him.

Tom Latham, the captain of New Zealand says it looks like a good surface and is hopeful that can put a good total on the board. Mentions that what they did in Bengaluru was great but they had to switch quickly to Pune and nothing changes in this match as well. On being asked about New Zealand losing a series in Sri Lanka, and making a comeback in this series, Latham also mentions that Test cricket can be funny at times and believes that they didn't play that badly in Sri Lanka and says that sometimes, unfortunately, you can just fall on the wrong side of the result. Adds that they have tried to keep things simple and play their brand of cricket. Says there's a new opportunity in this game and it is all about adapting to the surface as quickly as possible. Informs two changes - Santner is out due to a side strain and Ish Sodhi comes in for him. Matt Henry is in for Tim Southee.
TOSS UPDATE - The flip of the coin lands in the favor of New Zealand and Tom Latham elects to BAT first.

PITCH REPORT - Dinesh Karthik and Murali Kartik are inspecting the Wankhede pitch. Karthik says that there is a bit of moisture in it and hence, it is dark brownish in colour. Adds that it is about understanding what happens when moisture is present. Kartik mentions that there will be a little bit of turn at the start and as the day progresses, it will get better to bat on. Also reckons that as the game progresses to the next days, it will take a lot of turn. Dinesh Karthik adds that there's help for everyone at Wankhede, as it always has been, and believes that the pacers will also get some initial help from the deck. Murali Karthik wraps up by saying that the captain who wins the toss will like to bat first.

India face their own pressure cooker. Six Tests left, with a non-negotiable mandate - win at least four to stay alive in the top two. This match is a psychological dress rehearsal before the gladiatorial challenge of the Border-Gavaskar Trophy. The hosts' commanding lead in the WTC standings has taken a serious hit after two shock defeats. One more slip-up, and they'll be playing catch-up when they head Down Under. This is their chance to forge their mental armor before cricket's most intense rivalry. So basically, one match. Two narratives. Infinite consequences. Who blinks first? Let’s find out together. Toss, pitch report, and teams coming up very shortly.

Survival, strategy, and stakes - this Test match is far from being a dead-rubber, but a high-wire act for both New Zealand and India. Reeling from a clean sweep against Sri Lanka, New Zealand has improved its PCT by taking this series home, but still stand at a critical crossroad. Fifth in rankings but still fragile. What seemed like a distant dream has suddenly sparked to life. Two stunning wins have transformed their WTC campaign from wishful thinking to genuine contention. Grab another victory in Mumbai, follow it up with a strong showing against England at home, and they could be eyeing their next WTC final appearance, but, conditions applied.

New Zealand on the hand, have done almost everything right. As spin to win is the mantra in the subcontinent, the Kiwi tweakers have been effective so far. The one who once wrote ‘Part time cricketer’ in his social media bio, has wreaked havoc. Mitchell Santner now stands as the highest wicket taker of the series, despite warming the bench in the series opener. His stints of 7 and 6 wicket hauls, respectively, in the second game has further elevated his stature in the team. With Southee and Henry complementing his magic, and Ravindra standing tall as the batting backbone, New Zealand aren't just playing cricket, they're rewriting the rulebook.

Amidst the rubble, Yashasvi Jaiswal stands tall as the lone beacon in the top order. Sarfaraz Khan and the middle order have shown glimpses of resistance, though questionable shot selection continues to haunt them. Washington Sundar has emerged as a silver lining, making the all-rounder spot his own with compelling performances. While the spin department holds its ground, the pace battery, despite Bumrah's presence, hasn't quite hit their usual menacing stride. The result? A team searching for answers on familiar soil where they once wrote their own rules.

The hosts have been rolled over and the biggest worry for them has been the inconsistencies in the batting department. And moreover, they have been vulnerable against what was considered their strong suit - spin bowling, that too, on home soil. While the coach Gautam Gambhir said their skills haven’t gone down against spin, the stats of this series state otherwise. Out of 40 wickets fallen across both matches, 21 were against spinners. That’s a tinge more than 50 per cent. Also, the form of the big guns has come under the scanner. While Rohit has two Test centuries to show for this year, it’s been more than two years since Virat scored a Test ton, and also in any format. Nothing to take away from these stalwarts, but it’s time for them to step up with more steeper challenge awaiting in the near future.

The stakes at the Wankhede Stadium couldn't be higher. While New Zealand eyes a historic whitewash, facing the possibility of their second-ever clean sweep in Test cricket. The only previous instance came against South Africa two decades back, in 2000 - a two-match series that, by a twist of fate, began at this very venue. Now, as the action returns to Mumbai's hustle and bustle, the hosts look to salvage pride and avoid the unexpected, while the Kiwis aim to pen down what would be their greatest Test triumph on Indian soil and rather, in their history of Test cricket.

India’s streak of a tremendous home dominance has been thoroughly challenged and breached by the Kiwis and find themselves in unfamiliar territory. New Zealand have already won this series, leading by 2-0. Winning Bengaluru, New Zealand won on the Indian soil after 1988, and the only third time overall. And then laying siege on Pune, displaying sheer dominance. Now, they possess the challenge of a clean sweeping the hosts in their own backyard.

The caravan of this 3-match Test series reaches to its final destination, also marking the last game for India on their home soil in this cycle of the World Test Championship 2023-25. On that note, we welcome all joining us for the coverage of the 3rd Test between India and New Zealand. We are in the ‘City of Dreams’ and the iconic Wankhede Stadium of Mumbai is all in readiness to host this immersive match.
... MATCH DAY ...

data.Series_Status: New Zealand lead the 3 Test series 2-0

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back to the third innings! The umpires are out to the middle and the Indian players circle in a team huddle before taking their fielding positions. The usual opening duo for New Zealand is also out to the middle. Devon Conway will be partnered by his skipper Tom Latham who will face Akash Deep with the new red cherry in his hand. Here we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Well then, this match is nicely set up and hangs right in balance with this late surge from New Zealand in this second session. It is moving at a very brisk pace as we speak. India do not have a very healthy lead in all fairness and their batting collapses have surfaced once again. But what's done is done. Now, they have the challenging task of restricting New Zealand from running away with the lead. New Zealand on the flip side will aim to bat throughout the day without losing many wickets as we still have 10 and a half sessions left in this Test. But, batting on this surface is not going to be a cakewalk for them either. As the pitch will further deteriorate, the Indian spinners will aim to extract more turn and bounce to ambush the Kiwi batters. A riveting next innings on the cards, folks! Stay tuned!

That's where the tweakers came in handy for the Kiwis. Ajaz Patel, in particular, redeemed himself with a spectacular 5-fer and ran through the lower middle order of India effectively, reducing them from a comfortable 180/4 to 247/9. He was very accurate with his lines and lengths. The ball gripped and turned prodigiously and Phillips too chipped in with a wicket along with Ish Sodhi and Henry too getting one. Washington Sundar though didn't lose up easily and counterpunched to extend of what was a very thin lead in India's bank. His quickfire 37 helped India to mark a lead of 28 runs before an unfortunate run out caused India's end. India couldn't get their lead of what was anticipated from them especially the way Pant and Gill were batting.

Cut to the second day. India had a mountainous task as they trailed by 149 runs with just six wickets in hand. Brushing off the collapse, Rishabh Pant and Shubman Gill constructed a monumental 96-run stand together with the former being customary to his approach. Both notched up their respective fifties and were also provided one reprieve each in the field. But as soon as Pant fell, the scoring rate dipped a bit and the boundaries were hard to find by. Shubman Gill was the next one to depart, missing unfortunately by just ten runs from his ton, and again, the India lower middle order was exposed badly.

After bowling out New Zealand within the first day on a not-so-challenging total of 235, India had a golden opportunity to continue with the momentum while batting. They did start well as Yashasvi Jaiswal looked composed for his 30 but moving towards the close of the first day, a dramatic collapse pushed India way back into the contest as they lost Rohit and Kohli quickly on cheap scores.

OUT! RUN OUT! An anti-climatic end to the Indian innings! Ajaz Patel lands this short again and around off, Washington Sundar steers it away through point and runs the single very quickly thinking there is a chance of a second run but he gives up that idea. However, Akash Deep is a bit late turn back, and Rachin Ravindra quickly charges onto the ball and throws it right at the top of the stumps where Tom Blundell collects and breaks the stumps in a flash. Akash Deep did not want to put a dive in and tries to drag his bat inside but the replay shows that he is short of his crease. Sundar is disappointed as he was looking good to extend this lead even further but now India have been bowled out for 263 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back to the post-Lunch session. The umpires punctually make their way out to the middle. The New Zealand players circle up in a huddle before spreading out to the field. Shubman Gill, unbeaten on 70, and Ravindra Jadeja on 10, to resume their innings for India. And it will be Ajaz Patel (13-1-76-2) to bowl the first over of the second session. Here we go...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

Well then, the first session has flown by in this second day and it hangs right in balance with a slight tilt toward the hosts. With a long batting lineup still to follow, India will be keen to get the lead in the second session and stretch it into a potential one. While New Zealand's goal will be to run through the lower middle order as they have done throughout this Test series. An immersive post-Lunch session will begin right after 40 minutes or so. Stay tuned.

Ish Sodhi was introduced to create an inroad against the two well-set batters, who love to play against spin. He did make an impact by removing Pant off a prodigious turning delivery that caught him off guard. India could well had been 7 down had Henry and Chapman didn't shell those easy sitters. However, Pant's wicket slowed down things a bit as the boundaries dried up and Jadeja and Gill batted with the aim to just see through the session together. But more importantly, even in a slowdown, India prevented any maiden over.

New Zealand, despite starting the day in a commanding position, were caught off guard when Ajaz Patel faced an early charge against him in his opening over. Their frustration only mounted when a couple of catches were grassed off Phillips' bowling. India capitalized on that and balanced aggression with caution to wrest back momentum. Ajaz Patel who looked well the previous day, had his lines and lengths disturbed pretty early on and hence, New Zealand leaked runs at an alarming in the first hour.

Both of them eventually notched up their respective fifties. But it was Pant who took only 36 deliveries to do so in his customary approach. His whirlwind innings brought India's deficit down to double digits in what seemed like mere moments. The ball was turning with variable bounce, but what Indian batters did here was use their feet effectively to negate any trouble. Rather than getting bogged down, they minimized dot balls, ensuring the scoreboard ticked along consistently.

The first hour of Test cricket often proves critical for the batters, and India faced a daunting challenge with their backs to the wall. However, Rishabh Pant made an immediate statement, especially relishing the contest against Ajaz. Brushing aside the previous evening's dramatic collapse, he launched into an eventful first over that set an assertive tone for India. At the other end, Shubman Gill settled in nicely, showing impressive defensive technique and benefiting from a vital dropped chance. The partnership flourished as Pant maintained his aggressive intent while Gill provided steady support.

LUNCH, DAY 2! Session Summary - 24 overs, 109 runs, 1 wicket. Aggression and resilience. All about the first session summed up. India would be mightily pleased to walk back into the sheds losing just a solitary wicket and effectively shrinking the deficit to just 40 runs courtesy to that 96-run alliance between Gill and Pant. New Zealand, on the other hand, leaked runs at an alarming rate of almost 4.5 rpo and need to regroup to strike back.

Halt. The spider cam is stuck just over the ground, and hence a slight delay. The umpires are waiting for it to move up. It seems to have malfunctioned and there are only about four minutes to go for Lunch. And just when the umpires called for Lunch, the spider cam started working, but the players had already started walking off the field by then. Pretty weird way to end an engaging first session of play.

OUT! A huge appeal for LBW and up goes the finger. Sodhi provides a huge crucial breakthrough for New Zealand. Rishabh Pant has a chat with Gill and just with a couple of seconds remaining on the timer, he signals the 'T' and challenges the on-field decision. Sodhi comes from around the stumps and lands fairly outside off. It pitches, grips and stays low and prodigiously turns back into the left-hander. Rishabh Pant goes on the back foot to work it to the leg side but gets beaten by the turn and lack of bounce. The ball passes close to the bat and pings his front pad. UltraEdge shows no spike and the Ball Tracking comes up with the ball hitting the leg stump on the umpire's call. OUT IT IS! Michael Gough, the umpire, gets it right yet again this time and this just might be the breakthrough the Kiwis were looking for. A celebration in unison from them as Pant departs on almost a run-a-ball 60. India are 180/5 down now, trailing by 55 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! Well, the first hour of this second day has flown by and not for a second it felt monotonous. Having the momentum against them, Rishabh Pant and Shubman Gill have effectively countered the challenging first hour and more so, they have dictated terms so far, blending in aggression with caution. On the other hand, New Zealand would be kicking themselves as they let the momentum slip and Gill's dropped catch furthered their frustrations. Ajaz Patel looked a bit off rhythm as his lines and lengths were disturbed early on. As a result, the deficit for India has now shrunk to 72 runs. India would like to go unblemished through the session while a couple of wickets here will catapult New Zealand back in the contest. An interesting next hour of play on the cards.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness now! The sun is shining brightly in Mumbai and we can see the players making their way out to the middle now. New Zealand are taking up their respective field positions while it will be Rishabh Pant and Shubman Gill to resume batting for India. Let's play...

A fresh dawn brings new possibilities - India must pick up the pieces and mount a comeback, while New Zealand aims to keep their foot on the pedal. As the first ball approaches, the age-old saying ‘morning shows the day’ could well determine which team writes today's story and dictate terms and conditions of this Test. Stay tuned as the first ball of Day 2 is not too far away.

In this game of competing outlooks, New Zealand sees themselves just six quality deliveries away from rattling India's batting order and containing their lead. India, meanwhile, believes they're a couple of responsible solid partnerships away from building a commanding position that could put them back in a strong position.

The Kiwis' bowling dominance in Mumbai is no surprise - they've already proven their mettle by skittling India for 46 in Bengaluru and then tearing through their batting lineup in Pune. This is just another chapter in their impressive run. And coming into the second day, we might possibly see more spin being deployed early on to ambush the vulnerable Indian batters.

Despite missing Santner through injury, New Zealand finished strong in the final half-hour. Ajaz Patel, after a streak of underwhelming returns, kind of found his rhythm back, striking twice to give the visitors a crucial late surge. And of course, Wankhede being his happy hunting ground, the old memories were refreshed from 2021 when he took all ten wickets here on this very ground.

As overnight batters Rishabh Pant and Shubman Gill resume India's innings, they'll need to navigate the crucial first hour with patience and composure along with dealing the grip and turn. The humid Mumbai conditions, which had already drained the visiting team on day one, will test their temperament as they look to build on their partnership.

Eight deliveries in fifteen chaotic minutes turned the game on its head. A series of self-inflicted wounds - poor shot selection by a set batter, a wasted review by a nightwatchman on a plumb LBW, and a needless run-out of the most impactful batter in the world - left India reeling. With Rohit and Virat's form woes continuing, the middle order now faces a mountainous task. Their mission - not just to match New Zealand's total, but to extend a lead that could prove decisive. With spinners finding increasing bite and turn, and Indian batters having looked vulnerable against the tweakers, the pressure is mounting faster on the hosts.

Hello and a very warm welcome to our coverage of Day 2 of this third and the final Test which is being played at the iconic Wankhede Stadium. India have already lost the series and their aim here is not only to prevent a whitewash but also win this game and maintain their position in the top two in this cycle of WTC. It’s the second day and we are already into the second innings where India trail by 149 runs, with only 6 wickets in hand.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, that is it from an exciting Day 1 of this 3rd Test. India needs to build up a few partnerships to get back in the game while New Zealand will back themselves to make early inroads and put even more pressure on the hosts. Day 2 will begin at 4 am GMT, but you can join us early for all the build-up. Cheers!

Ravindra Jadeja is up for a flash interview. He says that he feels special to take a five-wicket haul. He feels grateful that he got the wickets when the team needed a breakthrough, especially in the heat. Says that the team did pretty well collectively and also appreciates Washington Sundar. Says he bowled extremely well and everyone played their roles with the ball. On being told about him crossing Zaheer Khan and Ishant Sharma in terms of wickets in Tests, he says that he didn't know about that. Says he doesn't see how many wickets he has taken and only sees when he is not playing. Is really happy to make contributions and progress. On being asked about the pace at which he bowling, he says that you have to mix the pace here and you can't be too slow through the air. Mentions that there's variable bounce off the surface so you have to use your arm to get more revolutions. On being asked about the last 15 minutes of collapse in the batting, he says it was unexpected and says that miscommunication happens. Ends by saying that they need to build partnerships and need to take a good lead.

The last session pretty much belonged to India until the last 15 minutes. It didn't take long for them to wrap the Kiwis up with Ravindra Jadeja completing a brilliant five-for and Washington Sundar adding a couple more to his tally. Trailing by 235, India came out with positive intent but once again Rohit Sharma fell after getting to a start despite getting a couple of lives. The pitch though still turned and bounced a lot but Shubman Gill and Yashasvi Jaiswal mixed aggression with caution and didn't let the Kiwis bowlers settle in adding 53 runs together before the latter lost his patience and gave away his wicket to a pre-meditated shot. What followed was absolute chaos. Mohammed Siraj came in as nightwatchman but went back for a golden duck and took a review with him as well. Then Virat Kohli threw away his wicket calling for a non-existent run. India lost 3 wickets in the space of 8 balls and now Shubman Gill and Rishabh Pant will have to rebuild from scratch on Day 2.

However, things didn't go their way at the start because Will Young and Daryl Mitchell got settled and battled through the heat to keep the scoreboard ticking. They batted through the first hour with Young notching up a fifty as well. Just as when things were settling, Ravindra Jadeja came in and broke the 87-run stand and picked up one more in the same over. Glenn Phillips also couldn't stay for long becoming the third victim of Jadeja. However, Mitchell didn't give his wicket away, and despite being cramped up and struggling with the heat for himself to a half-century with the Kiwis being at 192/6 at the end of the session.

Winning the toss and electing to bat first, New Zealand would have liked to put up a few more runs on the board. They lost Devon Conway pretty early but the skipper Tom Latham and Will Young for them through that period. Akash Deep provided the early breakthrough but it took them a while to get the next. It was Washington Sundar who went bang bang towards the end of the session to put the hosts just ahead in the game.

SESSION SUMMARY - 129 runs and 8 wickets in 29.2 overs! A pretty eventful day of Test cricket! After a couple of shared sessions, it was looking like India were taking control of the game in the final session but New Zealand fought back brilliantly in the last 15 minutes of the day and made things even here going into Day 2. The hosts will be kicking themselves with how things panned out towards the end and it was absolute hara-kiri giving away the momentum to the Kiwis.
Pushed through flat and full on off, Rishabh Pant leans ahead and eases it to short cover for a quick single. AND THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 1!

OUT! DEAR, OH DEAR! RUN OUT! Almost a reminiscence of the Cheteshwar Pujara dismissal against Australia at The Adelaide Oval in the first Test in 2018, when Pat Cummins scored a direct hit from mid on to catch Pujara short at the bowling end. The batter and opposition are different this time but the result and the subsequent questions regarding the run precisely the same. In both cases, the call was questionable from the batter and the fielder was a fast bowler. Was the call made probably because Kohli felt that Henry might have been resting on his heels? And basically, was this run necessary at this stage of the day? Not sure. Kohli perishes too after a boundary. This is going from bad to worse now for India. A run out just at the brink of Stumps and Virat Kohli is absolutely animated with himself. Fuller in length, and at the stumps. Kohli got on the front foot and pushed it to mid on, calling through for a quick single. Matt Henry, at mid on was quick to pick and throw in a motion and scored a terrific direct hit at the non-striker's end. Kohli was compelled to put in a full-length dive to get home. The Kiwis started to celebrate and the decision was referred upstairs. The TV umpire confirms that Kohli's bat was just a foot outside the crease when the stumps were hit. It was Kohli's call so no one else could be really blamed. Heartbreaking last 15 minutes or so for India as they have now slipped from a comfortable 78/1 to a precarious 84/4. On the other hand, terrific from New Zealand to keep on fighting till the very end.

The physio rush out to attend the Kiwi wicket-keeper. Also, the umpires call in for drinks. Well, India's opening partnership dilemmas continue to haunt them as yet again, Rohit Sharma lost his wicket very early despite getting a reprieve. Rohit though played a few delightful shots before perishing but that's the most concerning part for India in this series - the opening stand failing to deliver. Shubman Gill too, has been thoroughly interrogated so far and is living on a knife's edge against the spin. Matt Henry filling in for Tim Southee has looked rock-solid with his lines and lengths and we might just see more spin as the day draws to a close. New Zealand would be pleased to get a wicket or two before Stumps while India's aim would be to prevent any further blemish to see through the day. An interesting hour or so left in the day now. Let's see how it pans out for both sides...

data.Series_Status: New Zealand lead the 3 Test series 2-0

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the run chase! The players are already out in the middle. New Zealand did not opt for the roller but India have and it will be interesting to see how the surface reacts. Yashasvi Jaiswal and Rohit Sharma are the two openers for India. Matt Henry to start proceedings with the ball. Here we go...
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

So, the magic number for India is 147 runs to avoid the whitewash and get a crucial win in the WTC cycle. Akash Deep struck in the very first over for India setting the tone for them. However, after that, it was all about the spinners. It was the star from the first innings, Ravindra Jadeja who troubled the Kiwis continuously and registered another fine five-wicket haul while his old partner in crime, Ravichandran Ashwin stepped up finally and bamboozled the batters with his carrom balls and ended up 3 wickets as well. Washington Sundar also chipped in with one. Now, it is up to their batters to apply themselves on a difficult wicket and chase down this total but the Kiwis will not make it easy and we are in for some thrilling action. Join us in a bit to see how things unfolds.

Just the 3 runs added in this morning and New Zealand have been bundled out for 174 runs. New Zealand came out to bat for the second time 28 runs behind and with the pitch deteriorating further, they knew batting was not going to be easy at all. Tom Latham got out early once again but it was Will Young who looked apart from the others. He held one end nicely keeping the scoreboard ticking but kept losing partners. He registered his second half-century in this game and added a crucial 50 runs with Daryl Mitchell. The lower order also added some important runs and managed to set up a target that was good enough to put on a fight.

OUT! IN THE AIR AND TAKEN! That's Ravindra Jadeja for you! Quintessential with the ball and he registers another 5-wicket haul. 15th of his Test career. Five in the first inning and five in the second as well. He has now taken 10 wickets in this Test and has effectively run through the Kiwi batting unit. India bundle out New Zealand under three overs in the day and they now need 147 runs to win this third Test. Coming to the ball, Ravindra Jadeja stays around the stumps and flattens the trajectory on the middle and leg, turning in off the pitch. Ajaz Patel sits down and premeditates the slog sweep. This Test match has been a fierce arm-wrestle, with both teams trading punches through the first two days. On this 'Moving Day', someone's bound to grab the bull by the horns and race to the finish line. Every ball could be worth its weight in gold, and you can bet your bottom dollar we'll have a result today unless we see some miracle happening. Who will rise to the occasion and steal the show? Stay tuned as the first ball is not that far.

As New Zealand clings to their final wicket with a 143-run lead, India has victory in their sights, but they just can’t get too relaxed and complacent. The game plan couldn't be simpler - strike early, snap this last partnership, and keep the target manageable on this treacherous surface. A quick breakthrough would not only limit the chase but also hand India's batters the mental edge as they prepare to navigate this spinning minefield. But, they will have to bat with absolute caution given how even their batting order has dramatically collapsed.

This is the kind of a surface where any target above 175 would be really challenging. As Ashwin said in the post-day interview that every run saved in this inning is going to be vital and it’s not going to be an easy chase. The pitch has revealed a fascinating pattern across the first two days. Morning sessions have offered relative comfort to the batters, but once the sun climbs higher, the spinners dictate the conditions. The numbers paint a stark picture - The first session of Day 1 saw just three wickets before 11 wickets falling in the next two sessions. Day 2 was even more dramatic - only one wicket in the first session exploded into a 14-wicket spree afterward.

New Zealand's batting woes mirrored India's earlier struggles, with wickets tumbling at regular intervals despite Will Young's composed half-century standing out as the lone bright spot. The lower order collapse - losing five wickets for just 71 runs - has put the visitors in a precarious position. Now, with O'Rourke and Ajaz Patel at the crease, every run becomes precious for the Blackcaps as they try to set a challenging target. Young's determined knock provided a glimpse of what's possible on this testing surface, but the rapid fall of wickets around him has left New Zealand hoping their last-wicket partnership can at least squeeze out some valuable runs.

India currently holds the upper hand thanks to a bowling masterclass, successfully containing New Zealand's attempt to build on their lead. The third inning showcased the artistry of India's spin duo, with Ashwin and Jadeja weaving their magic on a responsive surface. The pair has been nearly unstoppable, claiming seven wickets between them as they've carved through the New Zealand batting lineup and have resurrected the Indian hopes again. Yes, they have already faced the series defeat, but with a win, they will bank in 12 vital WTC points which will keep them alive in the top two and also inflate their PCT to an extent.

Welcome to Day 3 from Mumbai's iconic Wankhede Stadium, where we're witnessing a gripping final Test between India and New Zealand. This has been a fascinating contest that's ebbed and flowed very rapidly, with momentum swinging dramatically between both sides. The pitch has been far from typical Mumbai characteristics - offering sharp turn and awkward bounce that has kept batsmen on their toes throughout. It's shaping up to be a classic low-scoring thriller, with neither batting lineup finding their comfort zone against these challenging conditions.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, that is it from an enthralling Day 2 of this 3rd Test. India are slightly ahead in this game but as we have seen in this series, New Zealand will have their say and make it pretty difficult for the hosts to have it all their way. We are moving into Day 3 which is often called the 'Moving Day', and we are certainly going to get a result with a couple of days to spare in this game unless something extraordinary happens. The third day will begin at 4 am GMT, but you can join us early for all the build-up. Cheers!

Ravichandran Ashwin is up for a quick chat. He says he trusted his hands and went for that catch to dismiss Daryl Mitchell. On using the carrom ball, he says the wicket is itself divided into two halves. Tells it is responding differently from both ends. States that it is easier to bat from one end, and the batters also knew to take him on from that far end. Is hopeful that they will wrap things up with a couple of balls coming in the next day and also reckons that it won't be as easy to chase the target down either. But trusts his batters that they will do the needful. On being asked about the surface, he says it's a bit slow and he expected a lot of bounce on it. Adds it is not the typical Mumbai pitch and it is pretty slow in nature.

New Zealand knew that to just survive on this wicket was not going to work so they were proactive and looked for the runs. However, the Indian spinners were pretty good and kept on picking up wickets at regular intervals not letting any batters settle in. There were a few rash shots as well but the turning point was the stunning catch by Ravichandran Ashwin to dismiss Daryl Mitchell and break the 50-run stand. Will Young was the only one who looked settled and notched up a fifty as well. Glenn Phillips' quick-fire cameo took the lead past 100 but unfortunately for the Kiwis, they lost both of them in quick succession. It was the experienced duo of Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja sharing seven wickets among them and restricting the Kiwis to 171/9 at the end of the day.

In the second session, the game changed pretty quickly with New Zealand fighting back in the game. Ajaz Patel led the charge for them finally finding his consistency and picking up a fine five-for restricting India to just a 28-run lead. Shubman Gill missed out on a ton by just 10 but played a crucial knock for his side while Washington Sundar also added important runs toward the end. The hosts started well with the ball as well with Akash Deep getting rid of Tom Latham, but Devon Conway and Will Young got through the session with the Kiwis trailing by 2 runs at Tea.

India came out with a positive mindset and Pant taking 12 runs off the first over of the day set the tone. Shubman Gill and Rishabh Pant dominated proceedings in the first session registering their respective fifties and chipping away into the lead quickly. The Kiwis were taken aback by that onslaught and took a backseat to try and contain the runs rather than going for wickets. They were also not helped by the fact that they dropped both the batters of Phillips' bowling. However, the move to bring Ish Sodhi into the attack worked as he broke the threatening 96-run stand and gave the Kiwis a glimmer of hope before Lunch.

What a fantastic day of Test cricket! This game has moved at such a fast pace that we have seen almost everything happen and it is only the end of Day 2. New Zealand have huffed and puffed their way to a 143-run lead but have just one wicket in hand. India will be pretty happy with their performance and the game is tilting slightly in their favour, but with how the pitch is reacting, chasing wont' be easy at all.

Commentary.Commentary: The final drinks break of the day! Well, the hosts are well and truly over the Kiwis at the moment. The spinners have provided the maximum breakthroughs with the duo of Ashwin and Jadeja effectively undoing the batters. Ravichandran Ashwin in particular who had a pretty underwhelming series so far, proved to be the linchpin as he not only snagged a spectacular two-wicket haul but also grabbed a fabulous catch of the well-set Daryl Mitchell. Glenn Phillips tried to up the ante and did smoke a few out of the park but fell for his own aggression. New Zealand now lead by 103 runs but they need to add more to it. The challenge now is that they are into the long tail with only Will Young as the recognized batter. He has looked quite resolute through and through and a lot of responsibility now lies on his shoulders. India would like to get a couple of more wickets before the day's end while the visitors would be pleased to see through the day without any further casualty. Ish Sodhi is the new batter in for New Zealand at number 8.

OUT! TIMBER! Ravichandran Ashwin at his best! He has outfoxed Glenn Phillips with a beauty. He brings out the carrom ball here, full and lands it on the leg stump line, this one turns away sharply. Glenn Phillips fails to pick it and strides out to block but plays down the wrong line as the ball spins past the outside edge to rattle the stumps. Phillips falls for a quick-fire 26 off just 14 balls and New Zealand are effectively 103/6!

Commentary.Commentary: Time for another drinks break of the day! It is pretty neck and neck at the moment with New Zealand cleaning up the Indian lower middle order and then Indian bowlers effectively snagging three early wickets. The Kiwis currently lead by 46 runs and this partnership is going to be a pivotal one for the visitors. Will Young has looked solid for his 21, as he's been in this entire series with Daryl Mitchell providing a steady hand. The two together have put up a good 30-run stand and would aim to go unblemished towards the day's end. The way the pitch has behaved with prodigious turn and variable bounce, anything about 150 would be very challenging to chase down in the fourth innings. India would aim to bag at least a couple of more wickets to call it a day. Let's see how this final phase of the second day pans out for both sides.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for the final session of the second day of this third Test! We can see the Indian players in a huddle just outside the ropes and now they spread out to take their respective field positions. Devon Conway and Will Young to continue the batting for New Zealand. Ravichandran Ashwin to start proceedings with the ball. Here we go...
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

Ajaz Patel finally found his rhythm after Lunch and showed why he loves bowling at Wankhede. He picked the Indian batters one by one and ended up with an excellent five-wicket haul. Glenn Phillips also chipped in with one and from a position where they thought they would concede a big lead, they did well to keep it under 30 runs. The pitch did start to help the spinners a lot more making batting really difficult. The fightback from the Kiwis has made this game effectively a shootout of whoever bats well in their second innings takes the game. They lost Tom Latham early, but Devon Conway and Will Young steadied the ship and ended the session trailing by just 2 runs. They will want to continue the good work and extend the partnership while the hosts will hope that they can exploit the conditions in the next session and pick up a few more wickets. Join us in about 20 minutes or so to see how the final session unfolds.

SESSION SUMMARY - 95 runs and 6 wickets in 25.4 overs! Another exciting session in this Test and the game still hangs in the balance! India were well placed coming into this session but once again suffered a bit of a collapse which we have seen happen in recent times. From 203/5, they were reduced to 227/8 and their chances of getting a big lead evaporated quickly. Shubman Gill played well for his 90 but missed out on a ton. The lower middle order couldn't do much but a quick-fire 38 off 36 balls from Washington Sundar pushed India's lead to 28 runs before they got bowled out. The momentum continued with the ball as well with Akash Deep producing a beauty to get rid of the Kiwi skipper in the very first over.

A huge confident appeal for LBW but 'No' says the umpire. Rohit Sharma does not opt for a review. Pitches it on a good length, just outside off on the fourth stump line. It lands and skids through quickly off the surface and leaves the batter. Will Young rocks back and leaves it but the ball pings the back pad. The replays show that the impact could have been well outside off. And with that, it will be TEA ON DAY 2!

data.Series_Status: New Zealand lead the 3 Test series 2-0

Commentary.Commentary: Right then, that is it from this Test and this series as well. New Zealand clean sweeps India with some excellent performances in all three games. The trophy has been handed over to the Kiwi skipper, Tom Latham who joins his teammates and lifts it together, and poses for some pictures. The hosts do not have much time to think about this as they have a 4-match T20I series coming up against South Africa. The first game will be played on 8th November. New Zealand takes on Sri Lanka in the shortest format as well in a 2-game series with the first one scheduled for 9th November. As far as the WTC is concerned, India's next stop is Australia for the Border-Gavaskar Trophy starting from 22nd November while New Zealand will be hosting England in a three-match series. The first Test will be played on 28th November. But as you know, you can always join us early for all the build-up to every game. Until then, cheers and goodbye!

Tom Latham, the victorious skipper of New Zealand says that he is very ecstatic about this series win. Adds that the boys have done a very good job, and they were challenged with the bat and ball, but they overcame it. Tells that the seamers did the job in Bangalore and different players stepped up at different times for them. Mentions that in the last game, it was Santner and this time it was Ajaz Patel. Says that they wanted to come here and be aggressive with the bat and proactive with the ball. Further adds that they did not play that badly in Sri Lanka, but here they fell on the right side of the toss and adapted to the conditions brilliantly. Ends by saying that the girls winning the T20 World Cup was special, but this series win is also a very memorable one for them.

Will Young is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES for his consistent run with the bat in such tough batting conditions. Young says it is a massive win and is very proud of the boys. Says he just tries to keep it simple and trusts his defense a lot. On being asked about what he has achieved, he says it is about coming here and creating happy memories with the boys.

Ajaz Patel is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his incredible 11/160 in this game. He says that he might have to carry a little piece of this ground everywhere he goes. Adds that spin bowling is all about rhythm, and he did not find that in Pune but here he felt much more in control. Mentions that he was confident in the morning session on Day 2 but the pitch did not offer much. However, after Lunch, it started to turn more and he felt more confident using his shape guile. Says that Rishabh Pant put a lot of pressure on them, and he had to think out of the box to do something different against him.

Rohit Sharma, the captain of India is up for a chat. He says it is a bitter pill to swallow. Says losing a series at home is not digestible. Accepts that they didn't play their best cricket and that New Zealand totally outplayed them. Adds that they didn't put enough runs in the first innings in the first two Tests and were always behind the game. Tells that in this game, they had the lead but failed to capitalize on that. Adds that while chasing, it is important to build partnerships, which they considerably failed. Mentions they wanted to apply themselves in the game well but that didn't go as planned. Further adds that there are certain areas he focuses on when he goes out to bat, but it didn't come off this series. About the positives, Rohit says that Pant, Gill, and Sundar have shown how to bat on these kinds of surfaces and that you have to be proactive and be aware of what to do. Says this was an unfortunate series and admits that even as a captain, he wasn't at his best to lead the side. Ends by saying that they collectively failed as a unit.
Presentation Time...

Daryl Mitchell is up for a quick chat. He says it feels really special to win the Test match on such a historic ground and more special to clean sweep the world-class Indian side. On the surface, he mentions that they knew that it was turning a lot so they wanted to put pressure on the bowlers States they aimed to survive as long as they could and wanted to land the ball in the right areas and wait for their chances. Says they are just a bunch of Kiwis ready to take on the world.

Akash Deep struck early with Tom Latham’s wicket, but Devon Conway and Will Young battled hard to narrow the gap to 2 by Tea. Sensing survival alone wouldn’t be enough, the Kiwis batted aggressively in the final session, but the Indian spinners kept striking back. Ravichandran Ashwin’s brilliant catch to dismiss Daryl Mitchell turned the tide, and though Will Young’s fifty and Glenn Phillips’ cameo pushed the lead past 100, Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja’s combined seven wickets left New Zealand at 171/9, setting up an intense finale.

India started Day 2 with an aggressive intent, as Rishabh Pant took 12 runs off the first over, setting an electric tone. Pant and Shubman Gill both reached fifties, pushing the Kiwis onto the back foot as they scrambled to contain runs. New Zealand got a lucky break before Lunch when Ish Sodhi ended a promising 96-run stand. The second session saw a Kiwi comeback, with Ajaz Patel’s impressive five-for limiting India to a slim 28-run lead.

Will Young, continuing his rich vein of form, displayed exceptional temperament in crafting a well-made 71, while Daryl Mitchell emerged as the innings' top-scorer with a determined 82. However, the spin duo of Washington Sundar and Ravindra Jadeja proved too hot to handle on the responsive surface. Their exceptional bowling performance cut short New Zealand's aspirations of batting through the first day, restricting them to a modest total of 235. When India came out to bat, they had a huge opportunity to go past New Zealand's total, but there came a twist. More than a twist, a streak of unwanted shots, and a hasty run-out that reduced India to 86/4 at the end of the first day.

In what turned out to be a fascinating Test match, New Zealand's decision to bat first on the red-soil surface didn't quite go according to plan. The pitch revealed its true colors early on, offering significant turn from day one and challenging the Kiwi batter's technique against spin. Despite losing early wickets and finding themselves in a precarious position, the Black Caps showed remarkable resilience through a game-changing 87-run partnership between Will Young and Daryl Mitchell.

Coming into Day 3, we knew we would get a result but the pendulum shifted from one team to another and every ball was an event. New Zealand set up a target of 147 runs adding just 3 to their overnight score, but their bowlers were absolutely fantastic. Matt Henry with a great plan got rid of Rohit Sharma early and it started a collapse. The hosts found themselves at 29/5 in the blink of an eye. However, Rishabh Pant started a counter-attack and steadied the ship along with Jadeja for a while. He went on to get a half-century, but never really got support from the other end and once he was dismissed on 64, it was all New Zealand. Ajaz Patel shined with a match-winning six-wicket haul while Glenn Phillips supported well with three wickets helping to a victory by 25 runs.

NEW ZEALAND CREATES HISTORY IN INDIA! This is probably one of their finest-ever Test wins and we can see that from their celebrations and how much it means to them. They not only whitewash India here but also keep their chances alive for the World Test Championship final. It was once again, Ajaz Patel who came back to haunt them at his birthplace and he absolutely loves it here at Wankhede. For India, Rishabh Pant fought a lone battle and it looked like he would take the game away, but the Kiwis had other ideas and registered a special, special win.

OUT! KNOCKED HIM OVER! NEW ZEALAND BLANK INDIA OUT IN THIS 3-MATCH TEST SERIES AND EXECUTE A DOMINATING CLEAN SWEEP! History has been scripted at the Wankhede Stadium and probably the greatest Test series win in the history of New Zealand cricket. And this is the first ever time when India has been whitewashed in a 3-match Test series on their home soil. Absolute pin-drop silence in the stadium but exactly contradictory scenes in the visitors' camp as their joy knows no bounds. Coming to the delivery, Ajaz Patel bowls it from over the stumps, and tosses this one up. Full in length, outside off, and it lands right on the rough and spins back in viciously. Washington Sundar sits down to access the slog sweep but the turn gets the better of him. He gets no bat on it and the ball disturbs the furniture. Ajaz Patel finish off with a spectacular 6-for but this has been a complete team performance by the Blackcaps. They win this series by 3-0.

OUT! TAKEN! Oh dear oh dear! We have another twist in the tale in this game, Rishabh Pant is not happy with this decision but has to walk back. Ajaz Patel slows it up a bit, full and on off, turns in sharply with bounce, Rishabh Pant uses his feet and looks to defend but the ball passes close to the inside edge and pops up, Tom Blundell, the keeper gets forward and completes the catch. Another appeal for bat-pad, but turned down again! Tom Latham is desperate here and decides to take the review. UltraEdge shows a spike when the bat hits his pad, but there is also a spike when the ball is close to the bat and there is no gap in the replay. The third umpire overturns the on-field call and there is complete silence around the ground. Pant cannot believe it one bit, and has an animated chat with the on-field umpire, Michael Gough. But, it is done and dusted as the decision has been made and he goes back with the slowest walks to the dressing room, departing after 64 off 57 and this is anyone's game now. Boos all around the Wankhede as the controller of the game is gone. Ajaz Patel gets his 7th five-wicket haul, and each of them has come in the subcontinent. New Zealand can now sense history in the making as they are just 3 wickets away from executing a clean sweep.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back, folks, for the second and what could possibly be the final session of this riveting Test series. There hasn't been one dull moment in this series and this is turning out to be a perfect culmination. The crowd is absolutely electric at the Wankhede and why not! India's hopes rely well and truly on Rishabh Pant as he walks out to resume his inning with Washington Sundar. The players of New Zealand too, take their fielding positions after a brief huddle talk. It will be Glenn Phillips to resume the proceedings with the ball for the visitors. Here we go...
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

But India's biggest enemy? Themselves. Instead of playing smart cricket with singles and calculated risks, they opted for rash unwanted shots and paid the price. And those earlier lusty blows from New Zealand's tail - Ajaz and Henry each clearing the ropes once - now felt like decisive punches in this nail-biting contest. Twelve precious runs turned from footnotes to headlines in this gripping chase. Well then, the equation now stands as - India needs 55 runs for a consolation win, and New Zealand are just 4 quality deliveries away from executing the clean sweep on the Indian soil. Who will handle the pressure well? We will find out in the second session that begins in about 40 minutes from now. Stay tuned.

Ajaz Patel though couldn't step a wrong foot in this game. Just as Pant and Jadeja looked set to steer India home, Ajaz Patel broke their 42-run stand. Call it a huge slice of luck for Pant, as him playing his usual fearless cricket, had earlier survived a close call - Latham's decision not to review coming back to haunt the Kiwis. This reprieve turned him into a crisis man for India as he constructed a precious 50 which of course looked more than a ton.

While Latham's tactical field placements kept the pressure cooker whistling, with the field being crowded near the batter, Pant had other ideas. True to his fearless philosophy, he danced down the track fearlessly, launching boundaries at will. His aggressive intent, coupled with Jadeja's calm presence at the other end, started shifting the momentum gradually. The scoreboard kept ticking on with timely singles and doubles.

New Zealand were never going to go without a fight and that's exactly what happened. Matt Henry drew first blood early, but it was Ajaz Patel who truly ignited the Kiwi charge, claiming two massive scalps in his first two overs. With the Wankhede pitch playing tricks and dancing to the tune of the spinners, 147 felt like scaling Everest. Latham's masterstroke of introducing Phillips paid instant dividends - his golden arm striking in the very first over. Before India could even blink, their batting fortress lay in ruins - Rohit, Jaiswal, Gill, Kohli, and Sarfaraz were all back in the pavilion scoring only 19 runs between them. From chase to crisis, the game had turned on its head with New Zealand closing in on executing the most unthinkable.

With a target of 147 runs that seemed achievable on paper, India's victory appeared within grasp. However, their persistent opening partnership troubles came back to haunt them. Rohit Sharma's impetuous decision to play a rash pull shot led to his downfall, while Shubman Gill's misjudgment resulted in his dismissal for just one run. What initially appeared to be a manageable chase quickly transformed into a daunting task as India found themselves three wickets down inside the first five overs with Virat too making zero impact.

Staring at a challenging position with only one wicket remaining, New Zealand's last pair of Ajaz Patel and William O'Rourke aimed to show resilience at the crease. However, their hopes were swiftly shattered by the brilliance of Ravindra Jadeja, who capped off a magnificent spell with a five-wicket haul.

The players head for Lunch, but not quite sure whether any of the teams would be able to get anything under their throats. Superb last 20 minutes or so for India after a monumental collapse, yet again. The session would have well and truly gone New Zealand's way but Rishabh Pant proved to be the cog in their wheel and he stands as the lone warrior battling it out. And as long as Pant is there, India's hopes are alive, but still, hanging by a thread.

OUT! LBW! Glenn Phillips strikes in his very first over! It is pin-drop silence here in Wankehede as New Zealand are on top at the moment. Flatter delivery, full and on middle, angling in, Yashasvi Jaiswal takes a big stride forward to block. His bat and pad are very close to each other and the ball pops up towards first slip where Daryl Mitchell grabs it. There is a massive appeal and up goes the finger. Jaiswal takes the review after a chat with Pant. After a few replays and UltraEdge, the third umpire reckons that it has hit the pad and not the bat. However, Ball Tracking comes up with three reds and Jaiswal too has to walk back to the hut. India are 28/4 now!

Commentary.Commentary: Is that LBW? Yashasvi Jaiswal is hanging by a thread here as the umpire raises his finger. But he thinks there were two sounds and sends it upstairs. UltraEdge comes up. There is a spike when the ball passes the bat. But, it does look pretty close as now the umpire checks whether the ball hit his front pad first. After several rolls, the TV umpire deems that the ball struck the pad first and there's a gap between the bat and the ball. Onto Ball Tracking which shows three reds. OUT!

OUT! IN THE AIR AND TAKEN! A needless rash shot by the Indian skipper and Matt Henry strikes early for New Zealand. Hits the deck hard, on the stumps, skidding through quickly off the surface, Rohit Sharma tries to take the aerial route and goes for his favorite pull shot but without proper weight transfer on the back foot. The ball gets a bit heavy on him as well as he goes through the shot. Mistimes it badly in the air as it swirls up in the air off the bat's manufacturer sticker. It goes only as far as Glenn Phillips who runs a few steps backward and takes a good reverse cup tumbling catch at the mid-wicket region. Disappointing shot by Rohit, to say the least. Commentary.Commentary: Spin from the other end and as expected it is Ajaz Patel.
Short and just around off, Rohit Sharma gets on his toes and punches it through cover-point for a single to end an eventful first over. 6 from it.

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Well, the first boundary and kind of an outrageous cricketing shot in the very first over. Short in length, on the middle, Rohit Sharma walks a couple of steps ahead and pulls it over mid on for a boundary.

Commentary.Commentary: This one jumps off the deck. On a good length, nipping back in sharply on the leg stump line, Rohit Sharma is completely taken aback by the bounce and misses to pull it to the leg side. Gets a blow on his body.

Commentary.Commentary: A huge, huge appeal for LBW but the umpire is not interested in this one. A long chatter between Latham and Henry but eventually they decide not to review it. Height must be the factor here but Henry will target Rohit's vulnerability here. Keeps the line of attack on the stumps, it slightly nips back in on a fuller length, Rohit Sharma is stuck in his crease and cramped up for room. Plays over the line and gets beaten on the outside edge. Ball Tracking after a couple of balls showed that it was going over the leg stump.
